---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About | GeekieNews"
  description="GeekieNews is a publication on AI software reliability by Oluwasegun Olumbe."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-16">
    <header class="border-b border-line pb-10">
      <p class="kicker text-accent">About</p>
      <h1 class="font-display mt-4 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink">
        Static analysis, never the model
      </h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-news mt-10">
      <p>
        GeekieNews is the publication arm of a simple thesis: when AI agents write
        software, deterministic analysis must sit between generation and deployment.
        Not vibes. Not self-review. Machine-verifiable checks with explainable
        evidence.
      </p>
      <p>
        I write about AI software reliability infrastructure: the harness around
        agents: codebase intelligence, contract drift, compliance controls, AI
        governance, and unified verdicts. The open-source toolchain (
        <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@nugehs/gate">gate</a>,
        <a href="https://nugehs.github.io/repoctx-web/">repoctx</a>,
        <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@nugehs/tieline">tieline</a>,
        <a href="https://nugehs.github.io/bouncer-web/">bouncer</a>,
        <a href="https://nugehs.github.io/aiglare-web/">aiglare</a>
        ) ships the tools. GeekieNews ships the argument.
      </p>
      <h2>What we publish</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Essays</strong>: architecture and philosophy</li>
        <li><strong>Audits</strong>: findings from running static analysis on OSS AI repos</li>
        <li><strong>Comparisons</strong>: how this approach differs from incumbents</li>
        <li><strong>Releases</strong>: tool changelog narratives worth reading</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>CMS</h2>
      <p>
        Content is managed with
        <a href="https://keystatic.com">Keystatic</a>, git-based and local-first.
        Run <code>npm run dev</code> and open <a href="/keystatic">/keystatic</a> to
        edit. Articles live as Markdoc in the repo; GitHub Pages builds a static site
        on every push.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://segunolumbe.com">Oluwasegun Olumbe</a>, London
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
